### 5.8 SCENE EXAMPLE LIBRARY (MANDATORY REFERENCE POOL)

Use the following as valid scene families the model can rotate through. These are examples to include in the prompt’s internal scene pool, not a fixed list. The model should also invent additional scene families beyond these.

**A. Physical Proof Reveal**

- Human holding a resume, document, receipt, certificate, bill, or printed proof toward camera  
- Large logos, icons, symbols, or question marks layered over the paper  
- Good for: jobs, tech, money, scams, applications, audits, credibility  

**B. Shocked Host + Environment + Bottom Objects**

- Host reacting in foreground  
- Relevant environment behind them (gaming setup, office, restaurant, studio, workspace)  
- Products, food, tools, or outputs arranged across the bottom foreground  
- Good for: reviews, comparisons, “I tried this,” experience-based hooks  

**C. Price Comparison Face-Off**

- Human centered between two competing items  
- Big price on left, big price on right, “VS” in center  
- Good for: cheap vs expensive, value gaps, budget vs premium, SaaS tiers, tools, services  

**D. Duo Lifestyle / Taste-Test / Experience Scene**

- Two humans in frame  
- One or both interacting with food, products, gifts, or experience items  
- Festive, travel, market, or lifestyle background  
- Good for: travel, dating, food, events, seasonal content, challenge formats  

**E. Map Explainer / Route / Destination Callout**

- Giant map background  
- Dotted route, arrow, or travel path  
- Circled destination or zoom target  
- Optional symbolic overlay: mascot, creature, vehicle, warning icon, or mythic visual hook  
- Good for: travel, geopolitics, migration, logistics, storytime, “how I got there”  

**F. Problem-Solution Career Explainer**

- Big high-contrast text block  
- Human on one side doing a thinking / concern / “listen closely” pose  
- Simple icons like phone, checkmark, graph, inbox, decline line  
- Good for: career advice, productivity, application fixes, “do this not that”  

**G. AI / Tool Opportunity Panel**

- Human host in foreground  
- Robot, software screen, dashboard, or futuristic panel in background/side panel  
- Text block tied to money, leverage, automation, or growth  
- Good for: AI tools, software, no-code, agency, productivity monetization  

**H. “Avoid This” Document Teardown**

- Enlarged crop of resume, spreadsheet, form, email, or UI  
- Arrow pointing at the mistake  
- Human making an X, stop sign, or disapproval gesture  
- Bold warning text strip  
- Good for: tutorials, mistakes, audits, breakdowns, critiques  

**I. “Hold Up” Reaction Frame**

- Tight studio shot  
- Human with hands up, skeptical face, or intense pause expression  
- Quote-style or reaction-style text filling the other half  
- Good for: commentary, hot takes, writing critique, persuasion, callout content  

**J. Chaos / Tabloid / Viral Shock Montage**

- Intentional sensory overload  
- Duplicate subject, giant emojis, oversized icons, faux camera overlays, chaotic props  
- Use for sensational “what is happening?” energy  
- Keep it non-graphic and platform-safe  
- Good for: reaction content, absurd stories, gossip-style framing, chaotic hooks  

**K. Empty Wallet / Lack vs Dream Outcome**

- Human holding wallet, bill, empty hand, or proof of lack in foreground  
- Aspirational destination / lifestyle / result scene behind  
- Good for: money, travel, budgeting, side hustles, transformation hooks  

**L. Blur-the-Mistake Background**

- Document or screen blurred in background  
- Red X marks or error markers on top  
- Human reacting in foreground  
- Good for: resume mistakes, bad landing pages, broken copy, UI critique, ad review  

**M. Social Proof / Quote Card + Face**

- Tweet, post, DM, review, or quote card on one side  
- Human face large on the other side reacting to or amplifying the message  
- Good for: authority, wake-up calls, opinions, market commentary, quote breakdowns  

**N. Zoomed Crop + Presenter**

- Main asset visible in frame  
- Separate zoom box or crop panel highlighting one critical detail  
- Presenter points, reacts, or blocks the bad area  
- Good for: resumes, copy, offers, ads, analytics, product pages, spreadsheets  

**O. Bottom-Spread Product Table**

- Human above or behind a row of food/products/tools spread across bottom  
- Good for: comparisons, “best tools,” haul-style videos, reviews, challenge formats  

**P. Scenic Composite + Giant Headline**

- Large travel or lifestyle background  
- Subject cutout foreground  
- Giant headline in the top/right/top-center zone  
- Good for: travel, freedom, lifestyle, finance, personal story, relocation  

The model must treat these as **starter scene families** and generate additional ones using the same logic.

